{
    "analysis": "We have loaded and inspected metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv. All non-empty files cover minute-aligned timestamps from 2024-01-17T02:11:00Z to 2024-01-17T02:35:00Z, which lies inside the incident window (2024-01-17 02:08:52 to 2024-01-17 02:38:52 UTC). error_logs.csv is empty. Next we must follow preprocess -> anomaly detection -> fault identification -> root cause localization, focusing on the allowed candidate services: checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice. To narrow candidates, we should compute global thresholds per component-KPI over the full available series and then detect anomalies in the incident window.", 
    "completed": "False", 
    "instruction": "For metric.csv, restrict to cmdb_id in [checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice]. For each unique pair (cmdb_id, kpi_name): 1) compute the global P95 threshold using the full available series for that pair (do NOT restrict to the incident window when computing P95); 2) filter the metric points to the incident window (timestamps between 2024-01-17 02:08:52 and 2024-01-17 02:38:52 UTC) and count how many points in that window exceed or equal the P95 threshold; 3) for each pair report a compact row with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95_threshold, count_anomalies_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_unix (or NaN if none), max_value_in_window, max_over_threshold_ratio = (max_value_in_window - p95_threshold)/p95_threshold (or NaN if no anomaly). Return only rows where count_anomalies_in_window > 0, sorted by count_anomalies_in_window descending, limit to top 20 rows. Also return a short list of all (cmdb_id, unique kpi_name) combinations discovered for these five services (compact). Keep outputs bounded and textual only."
}

{
    "analysis": "We scanned metrics for the five candidate services and found multiple metric-level anomalies inside the incident window. The strongest metric deviations (highest max_over_threshold_ratio) are: emailservice.mem (~0.46), checkoutservice.mem (~0.44), and checkoutservice.socket (~0.40). Many other metrics show small excursions or p95==0 sparse signals (diskio/error). The next step is trace analysis to determine call chains and which faulty service is most downstream in traces. According to the workflow, we must (1) compute global thresholds per trace_name across the full trace.csv series, (2) detect anomalies in the incident window, and (3) inspect which services (cmdb_id) and which incoming callers (trace_name patterns like trace.from_X) show anomalous trace-level behavior. This will help decide which faulty service is the last faulty service in the call chain and thus the root cause component.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From trace.csv, restrict to cmdb_id in [checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice]. For each unique pair (cmdb_id, trace_name): 1) compute the global P95 threshold using the full available series for that pair (do NOT restrict to the incident window); 2) filter trace points to the incident window (timestamps between 2024-01-17 02:08:52 and 2024-01-17 02:38:52 UTC) and count points exceeding or equal to the P95 threshold; 3) for pairs with count_anomalies_in_window > 0, return a compact table limited to top 20 rows sorted by count_anomalies_in_window descending with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, p95_threshold, count_anomalies_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_unix (or NaN), max_value_in_window, max_over_threshold_ratio = (max_value_in_window - p95_threshold)/p95_threshold (or NaN if p95==0). Additionally, return a short deduplicated list of caller services parsed from trace_name patterns (extract the substring after 'trace.from_' and before the next '.' for trace_name entries) observed among anomaly rows. Keep outputs bounded and textual only."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric-level anomaly scanning and trace-level scanning for the five candidate services. Metric analysis found prominent deviations in memory and socket KPIs for checkoutservice and emailservice (emailservice.mem ~+46% over P95, checkoutservice.mem ~+44%, checkoutservice.socket ~+40%). Many diskio/error and trace.error_rate series have global P95==0, making those trace anomalies ambiguous. Traces did not provide clear non-zero error signals (error_rate p95==0 and max==0), so we cannot rely on trace error_rate to pick the root service. error_logs.csv is empty. According to the workflow, the next step is log analysis to disambiguate resource-level reasons and confirm which faulty service is most downstream and actually exhibiting faults at the incident time (around 2024-01-17T02:11:00Z). Logs (log.error_count, log.row_count) may show error spikes or other indicators (e.g., socket errors) to confirm whether the metric anomalies correspond to real failures and to identify the failure reason (high memory, socket error, etc.).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From log.csv, restrict to cmdb_id in [checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice]. For each unique (cmdb_id, log_name): 1) compute the global P95 threshold using the full available series for that pair (do NOT restrict to the incident window); 2) filter log points to the incident window (timestamps between 2024-01-17 02:08:52 and 2024-01-17 02:38:52 UTC) and count how many points in that window are >= the P95 threshold; 3) return only rows where count_anomalies_in_window > 0 with columns: cmdb_id, log_name, p95_threshold, count_anomalies_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_unix (or NaN), max_value_in_window, max_over_threshold_ratio = (max_value_in_window - p95_threshold)/p95_threshold (or NaN if p95==0). Sort by count_anomalies_in_window descending and limit to top 20 rows. Additionally, identify the top two cmdb_id with the largest total count_anomalies_in_window and return up to 10 raw log rows (timestamp, cmdb_id, log_name, value) for each of those two services within the incident window, sorted by timestamp ascending. Keep outputs compact and textual only."
}

